# No One-Liner Functions

Do not extract a named function when the body is a single expression with no meaningful reuse or abstraction.

Prefer inlining the expression at the call site, or using a named constant when the value itself is reusable (e.g. a regex).

```typescript
// ❌ BAD — function only wraps one expression
function isChessDotComAnalysisPath(pathname: string): boolean {
  return /^\/analysis\/game\/live\/\d+/i.test(pathname);
}

if (isChessDotComAnalysisPath(locationLike.pathname)) return true;

// ✅ GOOD — inline at the call site
if (/^\/analysis\/game\/live\/\d+/i.test(locationLike.pathname)) return true;

// ✅ GOOD — named constant when the pattern itself is reused
const CHESSCOM_ANALYSIS_PATH = /^\/analysis\/game\/live\/\d+/i;

if (CHESSCOM_ANALYSIS_PATH.test(locationLike.pathname)) return true;
```

Extract a function only when it:

- Has non-trivial logic (multiple statements, branching, or non-obvious behavior)
- Is reused in multiple places and naming the operation clarifies intent
- Needs shared documentation or a stable public API
